<p>Armed men stormed St. Mary’s School, a Catholic institution, in the Papiri community of Agwara Local Government Area, Niger state, early Friday, abducting students and staff. Authorities said at least 52 people were taken and one person was shot [apnews.com#1][nytimes.com#1][thehindu.com#1]. Residents fear the toll could be higher, with some estimating close to 100 victims [bbc.com#1]. Police and military units have been deployed to search for the missing in what is the second school abduction in Nigeria this week, following the kidnapping of 25 schoolgirls from a secondary school in northwestern Nigeria earlier this week [dw.com#1][aljazeera.com#1][nytimes.com#1].</p><img src='https://kagiproxy.com/img/yEC_aDG-5LuzXR2OSjQ7GqA2CtMs32ZRgvuaDA2T5HeXFXHFuZ5__-NRrwhBqB17Ktn2ZPP2ovAYgJ4lxh1CmT63JDDcPwmOK6SqfvniU5tq8BK_gqQ3P2R4hHsTc2Btm9qASkfNwDsW3Ql8T9rdmeFOvYYg16kbkULGPZi7B56iYqXwAWeN-684uh4' alt='Security presence outside a Nigerian school after a week of abductions in neighboring states.' /><br /><h3>Highlights:</h3><ul><li>Where it happened: The attack targeted St. Mary’s School in the Papiri community of Agwara Local Government Area, Niger state, affecting both pupils and staff [thehindu.com#1][allafrica.com#1][allafrica.com#2].</li><li>Numbers uncertain: Officials reported at least 52 abducted and one person shot, while residents fear close to 100 may have been taken [apnews.com#1][nytimes.com#1][bbc.com#1].</li><li>Security response: Police and military forces were deployed to search for the missing following the raid [dw.com#1].</li><li>State’s stance: The Niger state government confirmed an unverified number of pupils and staff were kidnapped and criticized the school for allegedly ignoring a security directive [allafrica.com#2].</li><li>Second case this week: The abduction follows a separate kidnapping of 25 schoolgirls at a secondary school in northwestern Nigeria earlier this week [aljazeera.com#1][nytimes.com#1].</li><li>International context: The incidents come weeks after President Trump threatened military action over attacks on Christians—a “Christian genocide” narrative that Nigeria’s government rejects—while the White House has expressed concern about violence against Christians [theguardian.com#1][scmp.com#1][cbsnews.com#1].</li><li>Wider pattern: Recent reports note that criminal gangs have increasingly targeted schools for ransom, and there was also a deadly attack on a church service reported recently [ndtv.com#1][straitstimes.com#1].</li></ul><h3>Perspectives:</h3><ul><li>Niger State Government: Confirmed the abduction of an unverified number of pupils and staff and described the incident as avoidable, blaming the school for ignoring a security directive [allafrica.com#2]. (<a href='https://allafrica.com/stories/202511210267.html'>AllAfrica (Vanguard)</a>)</li><li>Nigerian Federal Government: Rejected the framing of the violence as a “Christian genocide,” countering claims cited to justify possible foreign military intervention [theguardian.com#1][scmp.com#1]. (<a href='https://www.theguardian.com/world/2025/nov/21/nigeria-reels-after-second-mass-school-abduction-in-a-week'>The Guardian; SCMP</a>)</li><li>United States Administration: President Trump has threatened military action over attacks on Christians, and the White House has expressed concern about ongoing violence against Christians in Nigeria [scmp.com#1][cbsnews.com#1]. (<a href='https://www.scmp.com/news/world/africa/article/3333717/nigerian-catholic-school-pupils-abducted-gunmen-second-attack-week'>SCMP; CBS News</a>)</li><li>Nigerian Security Forces: Police and military units have been deployed in search operations for the abducted students and staff [dw.com#1]. (<a href='https://www.dw.com/en/nigeria-gunmen-abduct-students-from-catholic-school/a-74831286'>DW</a>)</li></ul><h3>Sources:</h3><ul><li><a href='https://www.ndtv.com/world-news/explained-whats-behind-nigerias-latest-school-abductions-church-attack-9677222#publisher=newsstand'>Explai